	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>2A03 &quot;comes from an uncertified manufacturer&quot;</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><a href="http://hackaday.com/2015/03/12/arduino-v-arduino-part-ii/" class="postlink">Hackaday article</a> states that Arduino and Arduino are going to court, and 2A03* is in the middle of it. Plug an Arduino clone with USB vendor ID 0x2A03 and it'll say &quot;This board comes from an uncertified manufacturer. We won't be able to provide any support if it doesn't work as expected.&quot;<br /><br />In before kevtris rant on &quot;Tarduino&quot; and whining about nonstandard header gaps...<br /><br /><br /><span style="font-size: 85%; line-height: normal">* Not Ricoh's. I just thought it was amusing.</span>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Drag</b> [ Thu Mar 12, 2015 12:29 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: 2A03 &quot;comes from an uncertified manufacturer&quot;</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />So let me get this straight:<br /><br />Two companies relating to the Arduino device are fighting because they both want to be called Arduino. Company A is the original developers of the device, and Company B was originally the largest manufacturer of the devices, and then bought out by someone who previously co-developed one flavor of the device, and renamed to &quot;Arduino&quot;.<br /><br />Both companies are/were trying to sue the other over trademark infringement (I'd be pretty mad too if my manufacturer started selling their own stuff under my name without my permission, and obviously my manufacturer would want to force me to change my name so they could effectively steal my market), and now the Arduino IDE (developed by, I'm assuming, Company A) spits out a non-fatal warning (&quot;Hey be careful this is an uncertified manufacturer&quot;) when you try to flash a device that comes from Company B (whose USB VID is 0x2A03), but doesn't spit out warnings for the dozens of other counterfeit Arduinos.<br /><br />While this is going on, both companies have different plans for the devices and are taking them in their own directions. So, two different companies both called &quot;Arduino&quot;, designing two different versions of the same device with two different philosophies, while each company is trying to stomp the other one out.<br /><br />What a queer situation, I wonder how it'll turn out?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


